Any misreport (e.g., placing a safer/less-contested firm first) can only cause me to take a worse company when my top choice is still available, and it cannot make an already-taken company become available. Therefore, truthful ranking maximizes my outcome for every possible serial order given the fixed capacities.

With random serial order and sequential picking, my best strategy is to rank companies by my true preferences. Any attempt to “game” by moving a safer option up risks locking in a worse outcome when earlier positions could have secured Company_A, and it doesn’t improve my chances at Company_A since availability depends only on earlier seekers’ picks. So I submit my true order to maximize the chance of getting my top choice and, conditional on it being taken, my next-best remaining option.

This is a serial dictatorship: when it is my turn I get my highest-ranked remaining company from my submitted list, so I should order companies to maximize my own outcome conditional on availability.
